#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:311
msgid "Use Case B — Customer Support Bot with Authenticated Messages"
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:313
msgid ""
"**The problem:** Acme runs a customer support bot (`@AcmeSupportBot`). When "
"a customer writes \"my order hasn't arrived\", the support handler needs to "
"know _who is writing_ — their account, subscription tier, and open tickets. "
"Without identity, the bot can only reply generically. With identity, it can "
"reply \"Hi Maria, your order #4521 shipped yesterday and arrives tomorrow.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:318
msgid ""
"The support handler is a downstream service behind Mycelium. It cannot issue "
"JWTs or do its own authentication — it just wants to receive the message "
"_and_ know who sent it. Mycelium handles the identity resolution "
"transparently."
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:322
msgid ""
"**The solution:** Configure a gateway route with `identitySource = "
"\"telegram\"`. When Telegram sends an update, Mycelium extracts the sender's "
"Telegram ID from the message body, looks up their linked Mycelium account, "
"and injects their profile before forwarding the update to the support "
"handler."
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:327
msgid ""
"The support handler never sees unauthenticated messages on this route. If "
"the sender hasn't linked their Telegram account, Mycelium returns `401` and "
"the message is not forwarded."
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:332
msgid ""
"```\n"
"Customer (Maria) sends \"my order hasn't arrived\" to @AcmeSupportBot\n"
"  │\n"
"  │  Telegram servers POST the update to Mycelium:\n"
"  │\n"
"  ▼\n"
"POST /auth/telegram/webhook/a3f1e2d0-1234-4abc-8def-000000000001\n"
"X-Telegram-Bot-Api-Secret-Token: 4b9c2e1a8f3d7e0c5b2a9f6e3d1c8b5a\n"
"{\n"
"  \"update_id\": 100000001,\n"
"  \"message\": {\n"
"    \"from\": { \"id\": 98765432, \"username\": \"maria_acme\" },\n"
"    \"text\": \"my order hasn't arrived\"\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
"  │\n"
"  │  Mycelium verifies the webhook secret → confirms this really came from "
"Telegram\n"
"  │  Responds 200 OK immediately (Telegram requires this, or it will retry)\n"
"  │\n"
"  ▼\n"
"Gateway route (identitySource = \"telegram\") takes over:\n"
"  │\n"
"  │  1. Buffers the request body\n"
"  │  2. Extracts from.id = 98765432\n"
"  │  3. Looks up which Mycelium account has Telegram ID 98765432 → "
"maria@acme.com\n"
"  │  4. Loads Maria's full profile (account, tenant, roles)\n"
"  │  5. Injects x-mycelium-profile into the forwarded request\n"
"  │\n"
"  ▼\n"
"Support handler receives:\n"
"  POST /telegram/webhook\n"
"  x-mycelium-profile: <base64 compressed JSON>\n"
"  {\n"
"    \"update_id\": 100000001,\n"
"    \"message\": { \"from\": { \"id\": 98765432, ... }, \"text\": \"my order "
"hasn't arrived\" }\n"
"  }\n"
"  │\n"
"  │  Support handler reads the profile → finds Maria's account → fetches her "
"orders\n"
"  │  Replies via Telegram Bot API: \"Hi Maria, your order #4521 shipped "
"yesterday.\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:375
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[[acme-support-bot]]\n"
"host = \"support-handler:3000\"\n"
"protocol = \"http\"\n"
"allowedSources = [\"api.telegram.org\"]    # only accept requests from "
"Telegram's servers\n"
"\n"
"[[acme-support-bot.path]]\n"
"group = \"protected\"\n"
"path = \"/telegram/webhook\"\n"
"methods = [\"POST\"]\n"
"identitySource = \"telegram\"             # resolve identity from the "
"message body\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:388
msgid "Two fields are required:"
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:390
msgid ""
"**`allowedSources`** — before even parsing the body, Mycelium checks the "
"`Host` header of the incoming request. Only requests whose `Host` matches "
"this list are processed. This prevents an attacker from POSTing fake updates "
"directly to your service. Supports wildcards: `\"*.telegram.org\"`, "
"`\"10.0.0.*\"`."
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:395
msgid ""
"**`identitySource = \"telegram\"`** — tells Mycelium to extract the sender's "
"identity from the body (via `message.from.id` or the equivalent field in "
"other update types) instead of looking for an `Authorization` or "
"`x-mycelium-connection-string` header."
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:399
msgid ""
"If `allowedSources` is missing and `identitySource` is set, the gateway "
"rejects the request."
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:401
msgid "Important constraints"
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:403
msgid ""
"**The user must have previously linked their Telegram account.** Messages "
"from users who haven't linked return `401`. Consider having the bot reply "
"with a link to the Mini App where the user can complete the linking step."
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:406
msgid ""
"The `group` field still applies. Use `protected` if all you need is the "
"user's profile. Use `protectedByRoles` if you want to further restrict which "
"users can interact with the bot."
msgstr ""

#: src/10-alternative-idps.md:408
msgid ""
"Your support handler receives the **full Telegram Update JSON** unchanged in "
"the request body. The profile is injected as a header, not embedded in the "
"body."
msgstr ""

